{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480180"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.2,0.1,0.07,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"22"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33442"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/22"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18846"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"504"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43777"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33442"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman is under regular follow-up with her physician since she was diagnosed with irritable bowel syndrome (diarrhoea predominant). She is very compliant to dietary and lifestyle modifications as advised. She has kept on low FODMAP as well as lactose and gluten free diet and has avoided coffee and other gas-producing foods like carrots, beans and brussel sprouts since her diagnosis. She is a non-smoker and does not drink. An endoscopy and colonoscopy have already been performed as part of her initial workup for her bowel symptoms and are normal. Even after her healthy dietary efforts she still complains of frequent loose stools, urgency, and a sensation of incomplete evacuation or pain during defecation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer physician now considers starting her on a medication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amitriptyline","Mebeverine","Polyethylene","Lubiprostone","Rifaximin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIrritable bowel syndrome (IBS) is a chronic functional disorder of the gastrointestinal tract characterised by chronic abdominal pain and altered bowel habits in the absence of an organic disease. IBS is commonly classified into four main subtypes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiarrhoea predominant (IBS-D)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConstipation predominant (IBS-C)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMixed (IBS-M)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnclassified (IBS-U)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntidepressants have analgesic properties independent of their mood improving effects. Tricyclic antidepressants, via their anticholinergic properties, also slow intestinal transit time, which may provide benefit in diarrhoea-predominant IBS. In this instance, \u003Cstrong\u003Eamitriptyline\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate first-line pharmacological approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile antibiotics should not be routinely recommended in all patients with IBS, in patients with moderate to severe IBS without constipation, particularly those with bloating, who have failed to respond to other therapies, a two-week trial of \u003Cstrong\u003Erifaximin\u003C/strong\u003E can be given. Rifaximin is a broad-spectrum antibiotic with very low absorption that stays in gut lumen and prevents bacterial overgrowth. This is known to reduce bloating and diarrhoeal episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELubiprostone and polyethylene glyco\u003C/strong\u003El are both are used in constipation-predominant type of IBS. Lubiprostone is a locally acting chloride channel activator that enhances chloride-rich intestinal fluid secretion. Lubiprostone is used in patients with IBS with persistent constipation despite polyethylene glycol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntispasmodics that directly affect intestinal smooth muscle relaxation (\u003Cstrong\u003Emebeverine\u003C/strong\u003E and pinaverine), those that act via their anticholinergic or antimuscarinic properties (eg, dicyclomine and hyoscyamine) and peppermint oil reduce stimulated colonic motor activity and may be beneficial in patients with postprandial abdominal pain, gas, bloating, and faecal urgency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tricyclic antidepressants, via their anticholinergic properties, also slow intestinal transit time, which may provide benefit in diarrhea-predominant IBS.","When dietary and lifestyle modification and other therapies fail, a two-week trial of rifaximin can be given."],"references":["Camilleri M, Boeckxtaens G. Irritable bowel syndrome: treatment based on pathophysiology and\u00a0biomarkers. Gut 2023; 72:590-99.","Lembo A, Sultan S, Chang L, et al. AGA Clinical Practice Guideline on the Pharmacological Management of Irritable Bowel Syndrome With Diarrhea. Gastroenterology 2022; 163:137.","Yang J, Deng Y, Chu H, et al. Prevalence and presentation of lactose intolerance and effects on dairy product intake in healthy subjects and patients with irritable bowel syndrome. Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol 2013; 11:262.","Halmos EP, Power VA, Shepherd SJ, et al. A diet low in FODMAPs reduces symptoms of irritable bowel syndrome. Gastroenterology 2014; 146:67.","Drossman DA, Chey WD, Johanson JF, et al. Clinical trial: lubiprostone in patients with constipation-associated irritable bowel syndrome--results of two randomized, placebo-controlled studies. Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2009; 29:329.","Chapman RW, Stanghellini V, Geraint M, Halphen M. Randomized clinical trial: macrogol/PEG 3350 plus electrolytes for treatment of patients with constipation associated with irritable bowel syndrome. Am J Gastroenterol 2013; 108:1508.","Menees SB, Maneerattannaporn M, Kim HM, Chey WD. The efficacy and safety of rifaximin for the irritable bowel syndrome: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Am J Gastroenterol 2012; 107:28.","Bahar RJ, Collins BS, Steinmetz B, Ament ME. Double-blind placebo-controlled trial of amitriptyline for the treatment of irritable bowel syndrome in adolescents. J Pediatr 2008; 152:685.","American College of Gastroenterology Task Force on Irritable Bowel Syndrome, Brandt LJ, Chey WD, et al. An evidence-based position statement on the management of irritable bowel syndrome. Am J Gastroenterol 2009; 104 Suppl 1:S1."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18846"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18846"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-03-08T14:43:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T08:46:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"22"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33442"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relat